  "text": "We conclude this section with studying error detection with spherical codes. Generally error detection proceeds as follows: if the received vector y is contained in C, the decoder outputs y, otherwise its output is undefined. Clearly for any finite-size code C ⊂ S n−1 the probability of undetected error is zero, therefore we define error detection as a limiting case of bounded distance decoding and study the behavior of P as τ → 0. Since the code is a finite set, the cumulative measure of spherical caps about code vectors tends to zero if so does their angle. Hence the error probability P de (C) is determined by the decrease rate of the area of a spherical cap. Assume that C is a code with distance θ separated from 0 and distance profile b(θ). If τ = 0, then by [CITATION_1] we have sin",
